The path to nuclear disarmament
NEW YORK – Massive weapons of destruction and disarmament present one of the most challenging tasks that the world faces at present. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote the common good of all and find solutions to problems that transcend borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is a paramount general good.
My interest in this topic is partly based on personal experiences.
My homeland South Korea has suffered from the devastations of conventional warfare and was exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other weapons of mass destruction.
However, such threat scenarios exist of course not only in Asia.
Despite the use of atomic weapons being long considered taboo, disarmament remains merely an aspiration.
Is a taboo that applies only to the use of such weapons really sufficient at all?
When it comes to nuclear weapons, individual states make the most important decisions.
But the UNO plays a decisive role in this.
We offer a central forum where states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and teach in order to achieve our agreed-upon goals, and we advocate for these goals.
Most states have decided to forego nuclear weapons and have summarized their obligations under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
However, some states view such weapons as status symbols, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against an attack with nuclear weapons, which largely explains the estimated 26,000 existing weapons still in existence.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of atomic deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and giving rise to new risks of nuclear weapons being used.
The world is still concerned about North Korea and Iran's nuclear activities, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns through peaceful means.
There are also concerns that we may be facing a "nuclear renaissance," as nuclear energy is viewed as a clean energy alternative during times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this will lead to the production and use of more nuclear material, which must be protected against proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are巨大的. Let me correct that to fit English properly: The obstacles to disarmament are enormous.
But their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve in terms of costs and risks.
Let's translate the given German sentence to English:  "Denken wir an die ungeheuren Opportunitätskosten von hohen Militärbudgets."  In English, this translates to:  "Let us think about the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets."
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm International Institute for Strategic Studies), military expenditures rose last year to over $1.3 trillion.
Ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating that the total costs of nuclear weapons alone in the United States exceeded $58 billion, including future decommissioning costs.
This is, by any definition, a massive investment that could have been directed towards many other productive goals.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and the dangers inherent in them have sparked a global ideas revolution, breathing new life into nuclear disarmament.
We experienced the UN Arms Control Commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition, and Norway's Seven-Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan founded the International Commission for Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Citizen groups and states with nuclear weapons have also put forward proposals, such as the Hoover Plan, which was introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own Five-Point Plan.
Firstly: I call on all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, especially the nuclear powers, to fulfill their obligations under the treaty and to engage in negotiations for effective measures that lead to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they could negotiate an arms convention on weapons of mass destruction that would be supported by a strong control system, as has been proposed for a long time at the UN.
I have circulated a draft for such a convention, which provides a good starting point, to all UN members.
The atomic powers should actively engage with this topic together with other states at the UN Disarmament Conference in Geneva, which is the only multilateral disarmament negotiation forum in the world.
The world would also welcome a resumption of bilateral negotiations between the USA and Russia, with the goal of substantially and verifiably reducing their armaments.
The governments should also invest more in control research and development.
The proposal of the United Kingdom to hold a conference of nuclear powers on the topic of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should begin discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly make it known to the states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not become victims of a nuclear weapons attack or be threatened with such an attack.
The Council could also convene a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty should halt their nuclear weapons programs and enter into their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: One-sided moratoria on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials should only be allowed to a certain extent.
We need new efforts to bring the Nuclear Test Ban Treaty into force, as well as impulses for the Disarmament Conference to immediately and without preconditions take up negotiations on a treaty regarding fissile materials.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly endorse the efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
Moreover, I urgently call on all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty to conclude their safety agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily adopt the stricter safety clauses of the Additional Protocol.
Fourthly: The nuclear powers frequently circulate descriptions of what they are doing to achieve these goals.
However, these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like to ask the atomic powers to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and contribute to their further dissemination.   Note: The term "Verbreitung" in this context might better be translated as "dissemination" rather than "spread," as it is more commonly used in such formal contexts when referring to sharing or distributing information or materials.
The fact that there is no reliable estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons confirms the necessity for greater transparency.
And finally, various supplementary measures are required.
This includes the elimination of other types of weapons of mass destruction, new efforts against terrorism with weapons of mass destruction, a limitation of the production and trade in conventional weapons, and new arms bans, including for rockets and space weapons.
If there are real, verified disarmament advancements, the ability to eliminate the atomic threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the world's most deadly weapons and their components, we make it harder to carry out terrorist attacks with weapons of mass destruction.
These proposals offer a new beginning not only for disarmament but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
